The government’s plans are also a response to men whose feelings of shame over divorce led them to threats and acts of violence against their ex-wives and children, Jadwiga Emilewicz told Polish Radio Five.

In such cases, the woman will not have to reveal if her and her husband were divorced, her age, or her financial status to the police, she added. The minister emphasised that the new data provisions would not have been possible without the new Personal Data Bill.

“With the Private-Disclosure Act, a person can give up their personal data upon which another person might base a decision affecting their lives,” said Emilewicz. The minister explained that this was how a divorced woman, home alone, would be able to disclose that she was no longer married, and later, when she is in a relationship with a new partner, that information should not be disclosed to neighbours, employers or landlord without her agreement.

The new laws were presented by the government on Wednesday.
